AGI - An updated guide on ADHD, or attention deficit and hyperactivity disorder has been developed, which affects children more and is characterized by disrespect, disorganization, hyperactivity and impulsivity levels, so as to update the guidelines of the American Academy of Pediatrics and inform clinical practice. The new guidelines, published in Pediatrics magazine, were traced by researchers from Southern California Evidence Review Center, which is part of the USC Keck School of Medicine. Hundreds of ADHD studies are disseminated each year, but further insights are needed to ensure that these discoveries improve people's lives.> In general, scientists found that both drugs and psychosocial treatments work for the treatment of ADHD and children affected by this pathology can improve.
&nbsp;
"We have more research than ever on ADHD, but we have to recapture them reliably and validly," said Susanne Hempel, professor of public health and population clinics at the Keck School of Medicine and director of the Southern California Evidence Review Center, who supervised the work. The research group, which includes researchers from the Southern California Evidence-based Practice Center, the childhood psychiatrist division of the Keck School of Medicine and the Children's Hospital Los Angeles Behavioral Health Institute, examined more than 23,000 publications on the ADHD. The work was commissioned by the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality and funded by the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute.&nbsp;The results answer great questions to identify what is useful for diagnosing and treating ADHD effectively and indicate the gaps in research, including the most effective way to monitor the progression of the condition over time. The doctors selected by the American Academy of Pediatrics will now use the review to create updated clinical guidelines that inform the best practices in the care of ADHD throughout the nation.
