Before starting the literature review, the research team developed questions and protocols in collaboration with ADHD experts in the field, to make sure to ask and answer questions that could be of direct benefit to patients, families and industry operators. During the process, researchers also published preliminary results and welcomed comments in a period of 45 days. Researchers conducted extensive research that was not limited to diagnostic tools or therapeutic approaches already known for their effectiveness. From over 23,000 publications, researchers have selected 550 studies for final analysis. > The works were selected if they met the stringent equipe inclusion criteria, which gave priority to rigorous study drawings, such as randomized controlled research. Many tools are available to diagnose ADHD, including evaluation scales for parents and teachers, patient auto-reports, neuropsychological tests, EEG approaches, imaging, biomarkers, activity monitoring and observation. For different approaches, researchers found a substantial change in results, with studies indicating that a given method was highly effective and others indicating that performance was poor.
&nbsp;
"We are improving the diagnosis of ADHD, but research is still characterized by many variations," he said. Many treatments for ADHD have been rigorously tested, creating a solid basis of evidence for drugs, including stimulants and non-stimulants, and psychosocial approaches, such as changing behavior. Other non-pharmacological treatments analysed by the team of scientists are cognitive training, neurofeedback, physical exercise, nutrition and supplements, support for parents and school interventions. "The drugs have the most solid evidence to improve not only the symptoms of ADHD, but also other problems that often accompany him, such as opposite and disruptive behaviors," said Bradley Peterson, Director of the Institute for the Developing Mind of Children's Hospital Los Angeles and chief author of the review. In addition to reviewing evidence on diagnosis and treatment, researchers have explored what is known about the continuous monitoring of ADHD, concluding further research is needed. Publications will now be used to support an update of AAP clinical practice guidelines for ADHD, providing up-to-date advice on how to better diagnose, assess and treat the condition. "The general result tells us that ADHD is curable: there are many studies that show us that children can absolutely improve," he added.
